Kirizanshō dates back to the {{ill|Edo period|ja|江戸時代}} and is said to have been favored by the tea master {{ill|Kobori Enshū|ja|小堀政一}}.<ref name="沢"/> It was originally called sanshō mochi (山椒餅). The distinctive {{ill|sangoku|ja|算木}} shape became common during the late Edo period.<ref name="山本">山本候充編 『百菓辞典』 東京堂出版、1997年、71-72頁。</ref> Additionally, it is sold as a lucky charm at the {{ill|Tori no Ichi|ja|酉の市}} festival.<ref>[[小林信彦]] 『にっちもさっちも <small>人生は五十一から 5</small>』 [[文春文庫]] ［こ-6-18］ ISBN 978-4167256180、278-279p</ref><ref>小林信彦 『映画の話が多くなって <small>本音を申せば 9</small>』 文春文庫 ［こ-6-35］ ISBN 978-4167905354、245p</ref>
In {{ill|haikai|ja|俳諧}}, Kirizanshō is also treated as a seasonal word ({{ill|kigo|ja|季語}}) for the New Year.<ref name="春樹"/> {{quote|''Wakakusa no iro mo soetari kirizanshō'' [[Kubota Mantarō|久保田万太郎}}
