{{ill|Kirizanshō|ja|切山椒|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Kirizanshō|qq=}} is a type of {{ill|wagashi|ja|和菓子|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/wagashi|qq=}} (Japanese confectionery) traditionally eaten during the {{ill|New Year|ja|正月|1=Japanese New Year|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/New Year|13=User:Immanuelle/Japanese New Year|qq=}}. It is a rice cake confection made by mixing {{ill|Shinko (rice flour)|ja|糝粉|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Shinko (rice flour)|qq=}}, sugar, and ground {{ill|sanshō|ja|山椒|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/sanshō|qq=}} (Japanese pepper), or sometimes the essence extracted from sanshō in lukewarm water. The mixture is kneaded into dough, steamed, pounded with a {{ill|mortar and pestle|ja|臼|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/mortar and pestle|qq=}}, and then cut into long rectangular shapes resembling {{ill|Sangoku|ja|算木|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Sangoku|qq=}} or {{ill|hyōshigi|ja|拍子木|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/hyōshigi|qq=}} (wooden clappers).<ref name="沢">沢史生 「[https://kotobank.jp/word/%E5%88%87%E5%B1%B1%E6%A4%92-480237#E6.97.A5.E6.9C.AC.E5.A4.A7.E7.99.BE.E7.A7.91.E5.85.A8.E6.9B.B8.28.E3.83.8B.E3.83.83.E3.83.9D.E3.83.8B.E3.82.AB.29 Kirizanshō]」 日本大百科全書、2016th year 7月25日閲覧。</ref><ref name="山本"/>
The confection is often dyed in {{ill|Red and white (Japan)|ja|紅白|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Red and white (Japan)|qq=}}, but five-colored versions using {{ill|matcha|ja|碾茶|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/matcha|qq=}} or {{ill|kokutō|ja|黒糖|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/kokutō|qq=}} are also available.<ref name="沢"/><ref name="春樹">角川春樹編 『合本 現代俳句歳時記』 角川春樹事務所、1998th year 、1328-1329頁。</ref> A more luxurious variety, called {{ill|Nerizanshō|ja|練山椒|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Nerizanshō|qq=}}, is made by further steaming and kneading the dough after it is pounded, producing a premium {{ill|gyūhi|ja|ぎゅうひ|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/gyūhi|qq=}}-style confection.<ref name="沢"/>
Kirizanshō dates back to the {{ill|Edo period|ja|江戸時代|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Edo period|qq=}} and is said to have been favored by the tea master {{ill|Kobori Enshū|ja|小堀政一|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Kobori Enshū|qq=}}.<ref name="沢"/> It was originally called sanshō mochi (山椒餅). The distinctive {{ill|sangoku|ja|算木|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/sangoku|qq=}} shape became common during the late Edo period.<ref name="山本">山本候充編 『百菓辞典』 東京堂出版、1997th year 、71-72頁。</ref> Additionally, it is sold as a lucky charm at the {{ill|Tori no Ichi|ja|酉の市|1=Tori-no-Ichi|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Tori no Ichi|13=User:Immanuelle/Tori-no-Ichi|qq=}} festival.<ref>[[小林信彦]] 『にっちもさっちも <small>人生は五十一から 5</small>』 [[文春文庫]] ［こ-6-18］ ISBN 978-4167256180、278-279p</ref><ref>小林信彦 『映画の話が多くなって <small>本音を申せば 9</small>』 文春文庫 ［こ-6-35］ ISBN 978-4167905354、245p</ref>
In {{ill|haikai|ja|俳諧|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/haikai|qq=}}, Kirizanshō is also treated as a seasonal word ({{ill|kigo|ja|季語|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/kigo|qq=}}) for the New Year.<ref name="春樹"/> {{quote|''Wakakusa no iro mo soetari kirizanshō'' [[Kubota Mantarō|久保田万太郎}}
